.TH MYBTRFS 1 "June 2026" "mybtrfs 0.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
mybtrfs \- btrfs-native incremental backup tool (a Rust reimagining of btrbk)

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mybtrfs
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fICOMMAND_OPTIONS\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B mybtrfs
is a modern backup tool for btrfs subvolumes, written in Rust as a drop-in
alternative to btrbk. It provides atomic read-only snapshots, incremental
send/receive, and automated retention policies with a simpler CLI-first interface.

.B Key features:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Incremental backups via btrfs send/receive with UUID-based parent resolution
.IP \(bu 2
GFS (Grandfather-Father-Son) retention policies with dry-run preview
.IP \(bu 2
SSH remote support for both push and pull backups
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic btrfs drive discovery and selection
.IP \(bu 2
Safety-first: guards against common restore pitfalls (received_uuid trap,
delete anchors, verification on transfer)
.IP \(bu 2
Single static binary; no Perl, Python, or runtime dependencies
.IP \(bu 2
Full audit trail via optional journal logging
.IP \(bu 2
Per-run locking to prevent concurrent execution
.RE

.B Endpoints:
Targets can be local paths or remote SSH endpoints in the form
\fBssh://\fR[\fIuser@\fR]\fIhost\fR[:\fIport\fR]\fI/path\fR. Remote backups are
automatically discovered and mounted if accessible.

.B Stateless and idempotent:
Every run re-derives all subvolume relationships from live btrfs metadata
(UUIDs, parent pointers, received_uuid state). No side database or persistent
state files—snapshots are named with timestamps and collision counters.

.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-yes
Assume "yes" to all confirmations (e.g., creating missing directories).
Suitable for non-interactive use (cron, scripts, systemd timers).

.TP
.B \-\-journal \fIPATH\fR
Append a timestamped audit line for this invocation to the given file.
Journal lines record the command, arguments, and success/failure state for
auditing and observability. Journal write failures are logged but do not
abort the command.

.TP
.B \-\-lock \fIPATH\fR
Use the specified path as the run lock (default: \fB$TMPDIR/mybtrfs-$UID.lock\fR).
Ensures that only one mybtrfs process runs at a time. A second run that finds
the lock held exits immediately with code 3 (LOCK_BUSY). The lock is
automatically released when the process exits.

.TP
.B \-\-version, \-V
Print the version and exit.

.TP
.B \-\-help, \-h
Print brief help and exit. Use \fBmybtrfs \fICOMMAND\fR \-\-help\fR for
command-specific options and arguments.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B snapshot \fISOURCE SNAPSHOT_DIR BASENAME\fR
Create a read-only snapshot of the source subvolume.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISOURCE\fR
The source subvolume to snapshot (a btrfs subvolume path).

.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory that will hold the snapshot.

.TP
\fIBASENAME\fR
Base name for the snapshot; a timestamp (e.g., \fB20260624T123456Z\fR) and
collision counter are appended.
.RE

.TP
.B run \fISOURCE SNAPSHOT_DIR BASENAME\fR [\fITARGET\fR] [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
Full backup: create a snapshot, send/receive to the target (local or remote SSH),
then prune according to retention policy.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISOURCE\fR
Source subvolume to back up.

.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory that will hold the source-side snapshots.

.TP
\fIBASENAME\fR
Base name for snapshots (timestamp and counter appended).

.TP
[\fITARGET\fR]
Target for the backup: a local directory path or a remote
\fBssh://\fR[\fIuser@\fR]\fIhost\fR[:\fIport\fR]\fI/path\fR endpoint.
If omitted, you are prompted to select from discovered btrfs drives.
.RE

.B Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-incremental \fB{yes|strict|no}\fR
Strategy for incremental send (default: \fByes\fR).

.B Modes:
.RS
.TP
\fByes\fR
Use a parent snapshot if one exists; fall back to a full send if no parent is available.

.TP
\fBstrict\fR
Require a related parent snapshot; never fall back to a full send. Useful for
ensuring incremental-only backups in stable environments.

.TP
\fBno\fR
Always send full; never use \fBbtrfs send \-p\fR (no parent). Slower but
ensures independence.
.RE
.RE

.B Retention Options:
(See RETENTION POLICIES below)

.RS
.TP
.B \-\-snapshot\-preserve\-min \fB{all|latest|no|<count><unit>}\fR
Minimum keep floor for source snapshots (default: \fBall\fR).

.TP
.B \-\-snapshot\-preserve \fB"<schedule>"\fR
Tier-based retention schedule for source snapshots
(e.g., \fB"24h 7d 4w 6m 5y"\fR). Empty or \fBno\fR disables tiers.

.TP
.B \-\-target\-preserve\-min \fB{all|latest|no|<count><unit>}\fR
Minimum keep floor for target backups (default: \fBall\fR).

.TP
.B \-\-target\-preserve \fB"<schedule>"\fR
Tier-based retention schedule for target backups.
.RE

.TP
.B resume \fISNAPSHOT_DIR BASENAME TARGET\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
Resume an incomplete backup: re-send the latest source snapshot to the target
without creating a new snapshot. Useful if a prior backup was interrupted.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory holding the source snapshots.

.TP
\fIBASENAME\fR
Base name of the snapshot series to resume.

.TP
\fITARGET\fR
Target directory (local or remote SSH endpoint).
.RE

.B Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-incremental \fB{yes|strict|no}\fR
Same as for \fBrun\fR; default \fByes\fR.
.RE

.TP
.B prune \fISNAPSHOT_DIR TARGET\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
Prune snapshots and backups according to retention policy without creating
a new snapshot or transfer. Useful for cleanup and policy adjustment.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory holding the source snapshots.

.TP
\fITARGET\fR
Target directory (local or remote SSH endpoint).
.RE

.B Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Show what would be deleted without deleting anything. Useful for preview and
testing.

.TP
Retention options (same as \fBrun\fR):
.B \-\-snapshot\-preserve\-min, \-\-snapshot\-preserve,
.B \-\-target\-preserve\-min, \-\-target\-preserve
.RE

.TP
.B restore \fIBACKUP DEST\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
Restore a backup to a writable subvolume. If \fIDEST\fR already exists,
it can be moved aside (with \fB\-\-force\fR) or the command can abort (default).

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fIBACKUP\fR
The backup to restore (a read-only subvolume): a local path or remote
\fBssh://\fR[\fIuser@\fR]\fIhost\fR[:\fIport\fR]\fI/path\fR source.

.TP
\fIDEST\fR
Destination where the writable restored subvolume will be created.
.RE

.B Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-force
If \fIDEST\fR exists, move it aside to \fB<dest>.broken\fR or
\fB<dest>.broken.N\fR instead of aborting. Allows non-destructive recovery.

.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Show the intended plan (move-aside + writable snapshot) without making
any changes.
.RE

.TP
.B list \fISNAPSHOT_DIR TARGET\fR
List source snapshots with their correlated backups. Shows the inventory
of all snapshots and their corresponding backups (local or remote).

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory holding the source snapshots.

.TP
\fITARGET\fR
Target directory (local or remote SSH endpoint).
.RE

.TP
.B stats \fISNAPSHOT_DIR TARGET\fR
Show aggregate backup statistics: snapshot/backup counts, sizes, space savings
from deduplication, and compression.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory holding the source snapshots.

.TP
\fITARGET\fR
Target directory (local or remote SSH endpoint).
.RE

.TP
.B status \fISNAPSHOT_DIR TARGET\fR
Show backup health: snapshot and backup counts, the age of the latest snapshot
and backup, and health checks (e.g., missing or incomplete backups). Read\-only.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fISNAPSHOT_DIR\fR
Directory holding the source snapshots.

.TP
\fITARGET\fR
Target directory (local or remote SSH endpoint).
.RE

.TP
.B diff \fIOLDER_SNAPSHOT NEWER_SNAPSHOT\fR
Estimate the changed bytes between two snapshots \(em useful for sizing an
incremental backup before running it.

.B Arguments:
.RS
.TP
\fIOLDER_SNAPSHOT\fR
Path to the older (base) snapshot.

.TP
\fINEWER_SNAPSHOT\fR
Path to the newer snapshot.
.RE

.TP
.B list\-drives
List candidate btrfs drives for backup targets. Shows all discovered btrfs
filesystems with their mount points and available space. Helps with drive
auto-selection.

.TP
.B list\-subvolumes
List every btrfs subvolume on the local system, across all mounted btrfs
filesystems \(em the units you can pick as a backup \fISOURCE\fR. Output is
tab\-separated under a header row (\fBID PATH FS\-MOUNTPOINT UUID RO/RW\fR), one
subvolume per line; \fB\-\-quiet\fR drops the header for scripting (pipe to
\fBcolumn \-t\fR to align). Read\-only, but requires root (it runs
\fBbtrfs subvolume list\fR), so it exits with code \fB4\fR without it. Complements
\fBlist\-drives\fR, which lists the filesystems themselves rather than their
subvolumes.

.SH RETENTION POLICIES
Retention policies use a btrbk-style format with two layers: a minimum-keep
floor and tier-based schedules.

.B Minimum Keep Floors:
.RS
.TP
\fBall\fR
Keep all snapshots (default).

.TP
\fBlatest\fR
Keep only the latest snapshot (everything older is eligible for deletion).

.TP
\fBno\fR
No minimum; all snapshots are eligible for deletion per tier rules.

.TP
\fB<count><unit>\fR
Keep the latest \fN<count>\fR snapshots of age up to \fN<unit>\fR
(e.g., \fB24h\fR, \fB7d\fR, \fB4w\fR, \fB6m\fR, \fB5y\fR).
.RE

.B Tier Schedules:
A space-separated list of tiers, each \fB<count><unit>\fR. For example,
\fB"24h 7d 4w 6m 5y"\fR keeps:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
24 hourly snapshots
.IP \(bu 2
7 daily snapshots
.IP \(bu 2
4 weekly snapshots
.IP \(bu 2
6 monthly snapshots
.IP \(bu 2
5 yearly snapshots
.RE

Empty string or \fBno\fR disables tier-based deletion (combined with the floor,
only the minimum is preserved).

.B Units:
\fBh\fR (hour), \fBd\fR (day), \fBw\fR (week), \fBm\fR (month), \fBy\fR (year).

.B Example:
.RS
.TP
Keep all source snapshots but tier-prune targets to 24h / 7d / 4w:
.B mybtrfs run /mnt/data snapshots backup ssh://remote/backups/data \e
.B   \-\-snapshot\-preserve\-min all \e
.B   \-\-target\-preserve\-min latest \-\-target\-preserve "24h 7d 4w"
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B Full local backup with interactive drive selection:
.RS
.B mybtrfs run /mnt/data snapshots backup
.P
(You will be prompted to choose a local btrfs drive.)
.RE

.TP
.B Full backup to a remote SSH endpoint with tier-based retention:
.RS
.B mybtrfs run /mnt/data snapshots backup ssh://backup@remote:22/backups/data \e
.B   \-\-target\-preserve "24h 7d 4w 6m 5y"
.RE

.TP
.B Resume an interrupted backup:
.RS
.B mybtrfs resume snapshots backup /mnt/backup/data
.RE

.TP
.B Prune with dry-run to preview what would be deleted:
.RS
.B mybtrfs prune snapshots /mnt/backup/data \-\-dry\-run \e
.B   \-\-target\-preserve "24h 7d 4w 6m 5y"
.RE

.TP
.B Restore a backup to a writable snapshot:
.RS
.B mybtrfs restore /mnt/backup/data/backup_20260101T000000Z /mnt/restore
.RE

.TP
.B Restore from a remote SSH backup:
.RS
.B mybtrfs restore ssh://backup@remote/backups/data/backup_20260101T000000Z \e
.B   /mnt/restore
.RE

.TP
.B List all snapshots and their backups:
.RS
.B mybtrfs list snapshots /mnt/backup/data
.RE

.TP
.B Show backup statistics:
.RS
.B mybtrfs stats snapshots /mnt/backup/data
.RE

.TP
.B Non-interactive cron backup with audit trail:
.RS
.B mybtrfs run /mnt/data snapshots backup \e
.B   \-\-yes \e
.B   \-\-journal /var/log/mybtrfs-audit.log \e
.B   \-\-lock /run/mybtrfs.lock
.RE

.TP
.B List available backup drives:
.RS
.B mybtrfs list\-drives
.RE

.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0
Success.

.TP
.B 1
Generic failure (command failed, subvolume not found, send/receive error, etc.).

.TP
.B 2
Usage error (bad arguments, invalid retention policy, malformed SSH endpoint, etc.).

.TP
.B 3
Lock busy: another mybtrfs process is already running (lock held).

.TP
.B 4
Permission denied: the command requires root (btrfs operations need privileges).

.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B RUST_LOG
Controls diagnostic logging level. Default: \fBinfo\fR.

.B Values:
\fBerror\fR, \fBwarn\fR, \fBinfo\fR, \fBdebug\fR, \fBtrace\fR.

.B Example:
.RS
.B RUST_LOG=debug mybtrfs run /mnt/data snapshots backup 2>debug.log
.RE

.TP
.B SSH_KEY
If set, passed to SSH for key-based authentication on remote endpoints.
(Consult ssh(1) for remote authentication details.)

.TP
.B TMPDIR
If set, the default lock file is placed in this directory instead of /tmp.

.SH FILES
.TP
.B <tmpdir>/mybtrfs-<uid>.lock
Default run lock file (per-user, in the system temp directory).

.SH NOTES
.B Safety invariants:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Send/receive is always verified: the received subvolume must be read-only,
have a \fBreceived_uuid\fR, and have the correct \fBparent_uuid\fR.
.IP \(bu 2
Delete-safety anchors: the just-created snapshot/backup and the latest
common snapshot/backup pair are always preserved. Deletion is skipped
entirely if any target was unreachable.
.IP \(bu 2
Restore never flips read-only via \fBbtrfs property set\fR (which poisons
\fBreceived_uuid\fR). The only path to a writable subvolume is an
unadorned snapshot without \fB\-r\fR.
.RE

.B Statelessness:
mybtrfs re-derives all truth from live btrfs metadata each run—no persistent
state file, no database. Snapshots are named with timestamps and collision
counters; non-matching names are left untouched.

.B SSH authentication:
Remote backups use your system SSH configuration (typically
\fB~/.ssh/config\fR, \fB~/.ssh/id_*\fR, and ssh-agent). Ensure the remote
user has btrfs mount/snapshot/send permissions.

.SH SEE ALSO
btrfs(8), btrfs-send(8), btrfs-receive(8), ssh(1)

